'''Candlesby''' is a village in the [[civil parish]] of [[Candlesby with Gunby]], about {{Convert|5|mi|km}} east of [[Spilsby]], [[Lincolnshire]], England. '''Gunby''' is a hamlet about {{Convert|1|mi|km}} east of Candlesby.

The present parish church is dedicated to [[Saint Benedict]], and is a Grade II [[listed building]].<ref>{{cite web|title=British Listed Buildings|url=http://www.britishlistedbuildings.co.uk/en-196011-church-of-st-benedict-candlesby-with-gun|work=St Benedicts Church|publisher=English Heritage|accessdate=29 May 2011}}</ref>  It was built by E. D. Rainey of Spilsby,<ref>{{cite web|title=Lincs To The Past|url=http://www.lincstothepast.com/Church-of-St-Benedict--Candlesby/907930.record?pt=S|work=St Benedicts Church|publisher=Lincolnshire Archives|accessdate=29 May 2011}}</ref>  in 1838, replacing an earlier church that had become derelict.<ref>{{cite web|title=GENUKI|url=http://www.genuki.org.uk/big/eng/LIN/Candlesby/|work=Candlesby|publisher=GENUKI|accessdate=29 May 2011}}</ref> 

A school was built here in 1872, but closed in 1933 with only three children in attendance. <ref>{{cite web|title=Lincs To The Past|url=http://www.lincstothepast.com/CANDLESBY-PUBLIC-SCHOOL/886185.record?pt=S|work=Candlesby Public School|publisher=Lincolnshire Archives|accessdate=29 May 2011}}</ref> 

Ancient finds at Candlesby include a crucifix brooch, armour, swords, and a shield, believed to be [[Anglo-Saxon art|Saxon]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Pastscape|url=http://www.pastscape.org.uk/hob.aspx?hob_id=355279&sort=2&rational=m&recordsperpage=60&maplat=53.18353600&maplong=0.17636000&mapisa=1000&mapist=pc&mapilo=0.1764&mapila=53.1835&mapiloe=e&mapilan=n&mapios=TF454674&mapigrn=367403&mapigre=545412&mapipc=pe23%205ry|work=Candlesby|publisher=English Heritage|accessdate=29 May 2011}}</ref> 

[[Gunby Hall]] was built around 1700 for Sir William Massingberd, and was the former seat of the Massingberd family. The last in residence was [[Archibald Armar Montgomery-Massingberd|Field Marshal Sir Archibald Montgomery-Massingberd]]. Today the hall is owned by the [[National Trust for Places of Historic Interest or Natural Beauty|National Trust]], and is Grade I listed.<ref>{{cite web|title=Lincs To The Past|url=http://www.lincstothepast.com/Gunby-Hall--Candlesby-with-Gunby/228836.record?pt=S|work=Gunby Hall|publisher=Lincolnshire Archives|accessdate=29 May 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=British Listed Buildings|url=http://www.britishlistedbuildings.co.uk/en-196022-gunby-hall-candlesby-with-gunby|work=Gunby Hall|publisher=Lincolnshire Archives|accessdate=29 May 2011}}</ref> 

